# Local dev container (docker run/compose). For a Bzync Cloud deploy, the
# platform DOES seed these as the project's real env vars on first deploy
# (see BZYNC_CLOUD) — but any value literally "changeme" is replaced with a
# generated random secret at seed time, never passed through as-is.

# ── Bootstrap admin account (root) ──────────────────────────────────────
# GITLAB_ROOT_PASSWORD / GITLAB_ROOT_EMAIL are real, supported vars — but
# deliberately not set here. GitLab runs its own password-strength check (a
# common-password dictionary, not just a length minimum) during the
# first-boot seed, and this repo's usual "changeme" default fails it
# outright and crashes the container instead of just warning. Leaving both
# unset is GitLab's own default: it generates a random 32-character root
# password on first boot and writes it inside the container (see README.md
# for how to read it back out). Only set these if you want a specific
# password instead — it still has to pass the same strength check:
# GITLAB_ROOT_EMAIL=admin@your-domain.example.com
# GITLAB_ROOT_PASSWORD=a-genuinely-strong-password

# ── GITLAB_OMNIBUS_CONFIG ───────────────────────────────────────────────
# The one place to configure everything else — a Ruby snippet, semicolon-
# separated, passed straight to `gitlab-ctl reconfigure`. Not baked into
# the Dockerfile because Dockerfile ENV can't safely hold a multi-statement
# quoted string; set it here or in the dashboard instead. At minimum, set
# external_url once you have a domain — GitLab uses it to generate every
# link (clone URLs, notification emails, webhooks):
#
# GITLAB_OMNIBUS_CONFIG=external_url 'https://your-domain.example.com';
#
# Recommended additions for a small, resource-constrained instance (each
# disables a bundled service you likely don't need day one — cuts memory
# meaningfully on top of GitLab's own baseline):
#
# GITLAB_OMNIBUS_CONFIG=external_url 'https://your-domain.example.com'; prometheus_monitoring['enable'] = false; grafana['enable'] = false; gitlab_rails['usage_ping_enabled'] = false; registry['enable'] = false;
#
# See README.md for the full memory/CPU picture before deploying.

# ── Git SSH access (optional) ───────────────────────────────────────────────
# Enable "Git SSH access" on this project's dashboard first — it shows the
# exact host/port to put here (e.g. ssh -p 20005 git@your-app.app.bzync.cloud).
# Without gitlab_shell_ssh_port set, GitLab's generated clone URLs (shown in
# its web UI) advertise the default port 22 regardless of what's actually
# reachable. Append it to your GITLAB_OMNIBUS_CONFIG value above, don't set
# it as a separate line — GitLab only reads one GITLAB_OMNIBUS_CONFIG var:
#
# GITLAB_OMNIBUS_CONFIG=external_url 'https://your-domain.example.com'; gitlab_rails['gitlab_shell_ssh_port'] = 20005;
